      "content": "Calculating those exact numbers requires a full amortization schedule, which is quite detailed, but I can give you a good, rough idea. For a \\$400,000 mortgage at 6.5% over 30 years, the monthly payment is about \\$2,528.26. In Year 5, you'll be paying a significant chunk of interest, and by Year 25, you'll be paying much less interest because you've chipped away at that principal.\n\n**Year 5 Estimate:** Around 60-65% of your payment will be interest, and the principal portion will be the rest.\n**Year 25 Estimate:** By Year 25, the interest portion will be significantly lower, perhaps closer to 30-40% of your payment, and the principal portion will be the majority.\n\nRemember, this is just a ballpark figure, and the real numbers depend on the exact timing of your payments. It’s a good reminder that every payment is a little bit of work done.",
